Web App for Processing NHANES Accelerometer Data

Dane Van Domelen

January 14, 2019

Background (skippable)

Though released ~10 years ago, NHANES 2003-2006 is likely still the richest dataset with accelerometer-measured physical activity on a representative sample of Americans. There is still plenty that can be done with these data, and there will additional opportunities as more mortality data rolls inand it may roll in for another 75+ years!

Upon initial release, the NCI provided SAS files with the raw minute-to-minute accelerometer data, along with SAS scripts for processing the data (https://epi.grants.cancer.gov/nhanes_pam/). The NCI deserves a lot of credit for publishing these scripts. However, they have some limitations:

  • Users have to download 3.87 GB data files to their computer.
  • Users must have a SAS license.
  • The scripts only calculate a few basic physical activity variables.
  • The SAS scripts are slow (e.g. ~25 minutes to process just the 2003-2004 data).

As a result, many research groups wrote their own scripts to process the data according to their own preferences. I did this for a while, and then decided to create R packages to share my functions with other researchers. I developed accelerometry (Van Domelen 2018) and nhanesaccel (Van Domelen, Pittard, and Harris 2018); the latter has a function called process_nhanes which users can call to process the data with customizable settings.

The app

Most physical activity researchers are in fact not R users, so it occurred to me that my functions would be much more useful if they could be accessed through a web app. So, I created one using R Shiny (Chang et al. 2018). It is available here:

https://jhubiostatistics.shinyapps.io/process_nhanes_app/

Basically, the app provides a user interface for the process_nhanes function. The main benefit is that it allows researchers to fully process the NHANES data, and export a file for analysis in R, SAS, Stata, or SPSS, without any specialized software. All you need is an internet connection.

Heres a screen grab of the starting screen:



You can go through the sidebar links and select your preferred options



On the last screen, clicking Process Data will result in an underlying R session processing the data according to your preferences. And when data processing is complete, youll be able to download analysis files for R, SAS, Stata, or SPSS.



Bugs etc.
